							<h3 class="one">...meet</h3>
Lucy is a 3.2 million year old fossil hominid, a close relative of humans. Her species, Australopithecus afarensis, is now extinct. Lucy's official museum number is AL 288-1.  She was found in 1974 by a team of French and American anthropologists at the Hadar Site in Ethiopia. While today this site is a desert, three million years ago it was a large lake surrounded by trees. 40% of Lucy's skeleton was recovered, an astonishing feat for a fossil so old.   
						</div> <!-- close feature_text one -->
						<div class="feature_text two">
							<h3 class="two">Lucy</h3>
The bones of recovered of Lucy include pieces of the skull, lower jaw, ribs, vertebrae, arm and leg bones, and hip bones. We know Lucy is a female because the shape of her hip bones resembles that of modern human females. Lucy's knee also resembles modern humans, which is bent inwards and not straight like in chimpanzees. This is an indication of bipedalism, meaning that she walked on two legs. However, other bones suggest that she spent time in trees as well as on ground. For more information on Lucy click here. 
						</div> <!-- close feature_text two-->
